const faqs = [{"question": "Does soy actually lower testosterone in men?", "answer": "The bulk of clinical evidence says no: not at normal dietary intakes. A 2010 meta-analysis of 15 placebo-controlled studies and 32 reports found that neither soy protein nor isoflavone supplements significantly altered testosterone, free testosterone, or sex hormone-binding globulin (SHBG) in men. Some case reports describe hormonal changes at extremely high intakes (3+ servings/day for extended periods), but these are outliers and not representative of normal soy consumption. Asian populations have consumed soy as a dietary staple for centuries without population-level testosterone deficiency."}, {"question": "Can alcohol lower testosterone?", "answer": "Yes: this is one of the most well-supported diet-testosterone relationships. Acute heavy drinking can suppress testosterone production for up to 24 hours. Chronic alcohol use causes Leydig cell toxicity, increases aromatase activity (converting testosterone to estrogen), elevates cortisol, and impairs hypothalamic-pituitary-gonadal (HPG) axis signaling. Even moderate daily drinking (2–3 drinks/day) has been associated with measurable testosterone reductions in some studies. Alcohol's testosterone-lowering effect is one of the most evidence-based claims in this space."}, {"question": "Do mint and spearmint lower testosterone?", "answer": "Animal studies have shown that spearmint tea can reduce testosterone levels in rodents, and two small human studies in women with PCOS found that spearmint tea reduced free testosterone. However, there are no controlled human studies in men demonstrating that normal mint or spearmint consumption lowers testosterone. The anti-androgen effect observed in PCOS women may not translate to men at typical dietary intake levels. Occasional mint tea or spearmint flavoring is almost certainly inconsequential for male testosterone levels."}, {"question": "Does sugar lower testosterone?", "answer": "Acute glucose ingestion has been shown to transiently suppress testosterone levels by 15–25% in men, with the suppression lasting 1–2 hours after consumption. A 2018 study of 74 men found a significant decrease in total and free testosterone after a 75g oral glucose load. Chronically high sugar intake contributes to insulin resistance, obesity, and metabolic syndrome: all of which are strongly associated with lower testosterone. While sugar itself isn't 'anti-testosterone,' its metabolic consequences clearly are."}, {"question": "Should men avoid flaxseed?", "answer": "Flaxseed does not need to be avoided, but its effects on hormone metabolism are worth understanding. Flaxseed is the richest dietary source of lignans, which can increase SHBG and potentially reduce free testosterone. One case report described a man with prostate cancer whose testosterone dropped significantly on a high-flaxseed diet. However, moderate flaxseed consumption (1–2 tablespoons/day) has not been shown to clinically affect testosterone in healthy men. The fiber, omega-3, and cardiovascular benefits of moderate flaxseed intake likely outweigh any marginal hormonal effects."}, {"question": "What actually lowers testosterone the most?", "answer": "The dietary and lifestyle factors with the strongest evidence for lowering testosterone are: (1) excess body fat (adipose tissue aromatizes testosterone to estrogen), (2) chronic alcohol use, (3) caloric restriction and undereating (severe diets suppress the HPG axis), (4) chronic sleep deprivation (one week of 5-hour sleep nights reduced testosterone by 10–15% in young men), and (5) chronic psychological stress: elevating cortisol, which directly suppresses testosterone production. Individual foods have far less impact than these systemic factors."}];

